4. Oritur nobilis quaeſtie, ſays Danaeus, in his Chriſtian Policy;
Lib. 3. c. 6. Here ariſes a noble queſtion, Whether it be lawful for Subjects to change and alter their Government? Yea, whether it may be done by godly men with a good Conſcience? Yes, ſays he, It may; and his Reaſon is this, Reges ſummi
que Magiſtratus, Kings & chief Magiſtrates are the Vaſſails of the Kingdom & Common-wealths where they Rule; and therefore may be diſpoſſeſt and dejected, when they attempt any thing againſt the Fundamental Lawes thereof; and as it is truly ſaid, A General Council is above the the Pope; ſo the Kingdom or Peers of the Land are above the King.

